doc.after: The 1916-D Mercury dime, struck at the Denver Mint, is the key date of the series, with a mintage of 264,000Â pieces.[10] The low mintage is because in November 1916, von Engelken informed the three mint superintendents of a large order for quarters, and instructed that Denver strike only quarters until it was filled. Striking of dimes at Denver did not resume until well into 1917, making the 1917-D relatively rare as well.[38]
